picam-frontend (1.0.0+202606220931) stable; urgency=high

  * Fixed: bind() failure was never checked. When this frontend's
    configured http_port (often 80) was already in use by another
    process — including another picam service running on the same
    machine — bind() failed but the code carried on to listen() on an
    unbound socket anyway. Linux silently auto-binds that to a random
    ephemeral port, so the process kept running and logged "Listening
    on http://0.0.0.0:80" despite NOT actually listening there. A
    browser hitting that port would then reach whatever else actually
    held it, with no indication anything was wrong on this end.
    Real-world case this exact bug caused: picam-orchestrator and
    picam-frontend both configured for port 80 on the same Pi —
    picam-orchestrator won the bind, picam-frontend silently moved to
    an ephemeral port, and the browser's "Not found" 404 was actually
    coming from picam-orchestrator's (correct, by design) lack of a
    web route at "/", not from picam-frontend at all.
  * Now checks bind()'s return value, logs a clear FATAL message
    naming the exact port and OS error, suggests the diagnostic
    command to find the conflicting process, and exits with status 1
    instead of limping along on the wrong port. Verified by
    reproducing a genuine port collision (two instances on the same
    port): confirmed exit code 1 and the expected FATAL message.

 -- Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>  Mon, 22 Jun 2026 09:31:06 +0000

